name: â˜€ï¸ğŸ“¿ğŸ™ LINNEA
description: art account ; Linnea , she/her , biracial (black & white) , 25 , autistic
tweet: Also once deities develop their 'branches' they are considered to be sacred things, so their arms and hands are often covered. Holding a deity's hand is usually only done in prayer as well, or as a special honor!

name: â˜€ï¸ğŸ“¿ğŸ™ LINNEA
description: art account ; Linnea , she/her , biracial (black & white) , 25 , autistic
tweet: Dawa wasn't necessarily treated poorly by their peers and elders, but they often felt inferior and lesser regardless. Dawa didn't want to be the best, but wanted to be the best deity they could be personally. But even their 100% didn't feel like enough.

name: â˜€ï¸ğŸ“¿ğŸ™ LINNEA
description: art account ; Linnea , she/her , biracial (black & white) , 25 , autistic
tweet: Dawa, as a young deity was considered very weak. Deities usually begin to saturate colors in childhood (10-11) but Dawa was unable to. Thus they were often assigned menial tasks by the human monks, cleaning, gardening, maintenance etc.

name: â˜€ï¸ğŸ“¿ğŸ™ LINNEA
description: art account ; Linnea , she/her , biracial (black & white) , 25 , autistic
tweet: 'saturation' is represented by a deity's 'branches' or the arms they have. Each arm is tattooed with a different color and pattern. The more arms one has the more powerful they are considered.

name: â˜€ï¸ğŸ“¿ğŸ™ LINNEA
description: art account ; Linnea , she/her , biracial (black & white) , 25 , autistic
tweet: Deities of the motherland aren't extremely powerful. Their abilities are molded by humans who raise them. ex: a town needs crops, a deity is sent there and develops agriculture based powers by living there. This is called 'saturation'.

name: â˜€ï¸ğŸ“¿ğŸ™ LINNEA
description: art account ; Linnea , she/her , biracial (black & white) , 25 , autistic
tweet: ANYWAYS Dawa lore... Dawa is a deity from an isolated place up in the mountains called the 'Motherland'. A deity is "an entity colorless, weaved of celestial canvas and birthed to mortals." Meant to "Adapt, lead, and protect"
